# 07 - Stepper Motor Control (3 Modes)

## What it does
Controls a 28BYJ-48 stepper motor using three input modes.
A mode button cycles between Potentiometer, Joystick, and Button Step control.
Current mode and motor status are printed to Serial Monitor in real time.

## Hardware
- Arduino Uno
- 28BYJ-48 Stepper Motor
- ULN2003AN Driver Board
- Potentiometer
- HW-504 Joystick Module
- 3x Push Buttons
- Jumper wires

## Wiring

### ULN2003 Driver → Arduino
| ULN2003 Pin | Arduino Pin |
|-------------|-------------|
| IN1         | Pin 8       |
| IN2         | Pin 9       |
| IN3         | Pin 10      |
| IN4         | Pin 11      |
| VCC         | 5V          |
| GND         | GND         |

### Controls
| Component              | Arduino Pin |
|------------------------|-------------|
| Potentiometer wiper    | A0          |
| Joystick VRx           | A1          |
| Mode button            | Pin 2       |
| Step Forward button    | Pin 3       |
| Step Backward button   | Pin 4       |

## Modes

### Mode 1 — Potentiometer
Left of center = rotate backward, speed increases further left.
Right of center = rotate forward, speed increases further right.
Center dead zone = motor stopped.

### Mode 2 — Joystick
Push right = forward, push left = backward.
Distance from center controls speed.
Dead zone at center stops the motor.

### Mode 3 — Button Steps
Forward button = 512 steps forward (quarter turn).
Backward button = 512 steps backward (quarter turn).
Step sequences complete before accepting new input.

## Concepts Learned
- Stepper motor vs servo motor — precise step control vs angle control
- ULN2003 driver board operation
- Multi-mode control logic using a single cycle button
- Speed mapping from analog input to RPM
- Blocking vs non-blocking movement trade-offs
- millis() debouncing across multiple buttons simultaneously

## Library Used
- Arduino built-in Stepper library 